  <h2>Why a Drain Gurgles</h2>
  <p>
    Household plumbing is designed so that water flows down and out while air moves freely to balance
    the pressure — that's what the vent pipes on your roof are for. When something restricts that
    smooth flow, water and air compete in the pipes, and trapped air escapes past the water as a
    gurgle at whatever fixture is nearby. So a gurgle always means flow is being restricted somewhere;
    the question is where, and how seriously.
  </p>

  <h2>The Common Causes</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>A filling or full tank.</strong> When the tank is near capacity, the system can't accept
      water as readily, and the resulting restriction shows up as gurgling — often the first audible
      sign a tank is due. See <a href="/signs-a-septic-tank-may-be-full/">signs a tank may be full</a>.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>A partial blockage.</strong> Roots, grease buildup, or debris in the line between the
      house and tank can restrict flow and cause air to gurgle back.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>A venting issue.</strong> If the plumbing vents that balance air pressure are blocked or
      inadequate, drains can gurgle even when the tank and field are fine — a plumbing problem rather
      than a septic one.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>A drain field that can't keep up.</strong> When the field is struggling to accept water,
      the backup of pressure can reach the house as gurgling, usually alongside other symptoms.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Harmless Quirk or Early Warning?</h2>
  <p>
    Context is everything. An occasional, isolated gurgle with drains that otherwise run normally is
    usually low-concern and worth simply noting. Gurgling that's getting more frequent, or that
    arrives with slow drains, odors, or wet ground over the field, is a different story — that
    combination is often the system's early announcement that it's starting to back up, and it's much
    cheaper to address at the gurgle stage than at the backup stage. If you're already seeing a
    backup, see <a href="/what-to-do-when-sewage-backs-up/">what to do when sewage backs up</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>What to Do</h2>
  <p>
    If the gurgling is persistent or paired with any other symptom, have the cause identified rather
    than waiting to see if it clears. Because the sound can come from the tank, the line, the vents,
    or the field, an evaluation is what tells them apart instead of guessing.
    <a href="/request-service/">Request septic service</a> and describe when the gurgling happens (for
    example, after the washer drains) and any other signs you've noticed.
  </p>
